T1  - Poverty and Witch Killing
PY  - 2005
Y1  - 2005/10/01
DO  - 10.1111/0034-6527.00365
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 72
IS  - 4
SP  - 1153
EP  - 1172
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This study uses rainfall variation to estimate the impact of income shocks on murder in rural Tanzania. Extreme rainfall (drought or flood) leads to a large increase in the murder of “witches”—typically elderly women killed by relatives—but not other murders. The findings provide novel evidence on the role of income shocks in causing violent crime, and religious violence in particular.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0034-6527.00365
ER  - 



